<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="603" pageId="6" pageNumber="601" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[674,1211,944,1700]" box="[677,821,944,971]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[674,1211,944,1700]" lastBlockId="8.[111,649,216,1098]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="603" pageId="6" pageNumber="601">
Measurements and estimates of variation in character states are detailed in 
<tableCitation box="[884,964,1008,1035]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="3.[113,124,219,236]" captionText="TABLE 2. Morphological characteristics of the holotype and paratype of Pseudochrysogorgia bellona n. gen., n. sp. Abbreviations: n, sample size; rg, range; - x, mean ± one standard deviation." pageId="6" pageNumber="601">Table 2</tableCitation>
. Colonies are black and matte at the base, and are characterized by a dark metallic luster (
<typeStatus box="[833,927,1071,1098]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus box="[976,1066,1071,1098]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601">paratype</typeStatus>
NIWA16273 black; 
<typeStatus box="[740,829,1103,1130]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601">paratype</typeStatus>
MNHN-IC.2008-007 dark brown). Branching sequence, as defined for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti" authorityYear="1864" box="[1074,1209,1134,1160]" class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae" genus="Chrysogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="6" pageNumber="601" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1074,1209,1134,1160]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="601">Chrysogorgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="VERSLUYS J." box="[738,893,1166,1193]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601" refId="ref9581" refString="VERSLUYS J. 1902. - Die Gorgoniden der Siboga-Expedition. I. Die Chrysogorgiiden, volume 13. Monographie Siboga-Expeditie, 120 p." type="book" year="1902">Versluys 1902</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="CAIRNS S. D." box="[906,1044,1166,1193]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601" pagination="217 - 222" refId="ref8911" refString="CAIRNS S. D. 2002. - A new species of Chrysogorgia (Anthozoa: Octocorallia) from the Antarctic. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 115 (1): 217 - 222." type="journal article" year="2002">Cairns 2002</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="CAIRNS S. D." box="[1056,1113,1166,1193]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601" pagination="511 - 541" refId="ref8949" refString="CAIRNS S. D. 2007. - Calcaxonian octocorals (Cnidaria; Anthozoa) from Eastern Pacific Seamounts. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences 58 (25): 511 - 541." type="journal article" year="2007">2007</bibRefCitation>
) is 2/7R for the 
<typeStatus box="[751,847,1198,1225]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601">holotype</typeStatus>
, and irregular for the 
<typeStatus box="[1067,1166,1198,1225]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601">paratypes</typeStatus>
(see Discussion). Th e irregular branching pattern seen on the 
<typeStatus box="[753,845,1261,1288]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601">paratype</typeStatus>
is linked to the fact that the stem bifurcates and anastomoses. Th e distance between branches along the stem is regular, particularly on the 
<typeStatus box="[720,821,1356,1383]" pageId="6" pageNumber="601">holotype</typeStatus>
. Coenenchyme covers most of the upper part of the stem and branches and contains numerous sclerites. Th e stem is stiff, robust, and significantly thicker than the base of branches along most of the colony (proximal area: stem twice as thick as branches; distal area: stem and branches equally thick). Branches are stiff and stem from the main axis at nearly right angles. Order of branching is variable, mostly between four and six; the number of nodes per branch varies between 10 and 39. Branching occurs in multiple planes. The internodal distance and the angle between subdividing branches are regular. Axial polyps were not observed on the 
<typeStatus box="[113,210,279,306]" pageId="8" pageNumber="603">holotype</typeStatus>
or the 
<typeStatus box="[295,392,279,306]" pageId="8" pageNumber="603">paratype</typeStatus>
, and polyp occurrence starts on the second branch internode. Over half of the polyps lean to one side. Polyps appear to always be leaning in the direction of branch growth. They are on average as wide as they are tall and their size varies between 1.7 and 
<quantity box="[347,431,438,465]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="603" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
. Th ey are constricted at the neck, a character that seems to be exacerbated when polyps are left to dry. The arrangement of sclerites is detailed in the diagnosis of the genus. Sclerites do not appear tightly interlocked: while exposing polyps to bleach in an effort to remove the upper tissue layer covering the sclerites, these would fall off the polyp very rapidly (see Material and methods). All observed types of sclerites are warted; rods are more finely warted than scales. Scales have blunt extremities. Crosses (scales and rods with four rays in one plane) are rare but occur in the coenenchyme, body wall and tentacles. Most sclerites of the coenenchyme are scales and few are plates (for example, the fourth sclerite of 
<figureCitation box="[146,254,913,940]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[113,124,1657,1674]" captionTargetBox="[131,1192,215,1576]" captionTargetId="figure-20@11.[130,663,759,1305]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 6. — Pseudochrysogorgia bellona n. gen., n. sp. holotype, SEM of sclerites: A, branch coenenchyme; B, polyp body wall; C, tentacles. Scale bar: 100 μm." pageId="8" pageNumber="603">Figure 6A</figureCitation>
is considered as a plate). While the proximal part of the polyp body wall (anthostele) is almost exclusively covered by scales, the distal part is richer in rods. Th e longest rods are found at the base of the tentacles, while smaller rods are found along the back of the tentacles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
